a Merrill Lynch<br> Harlan Sur - JPMorgan<br> Ross Seymore - Deutsche Bank<br> Srini Pajjuri - CLSA Securities<br> Stacy Rasgon - Bernstein<br> John Pitzer - Credit Suisse<br> Timothy Arcuri - Cowen &amp; Company<br> Mark Delaney \u2013 Goldman Sachs<br> C.J. Muse - Evercore ISI<br> Doug Freeman - RBC Capital Markets<br> Craig Ellis - B. Riley<br> Blayne Curtis - Barclays<br> David Wong - Wells Fargo<br> Christopher Roland - FBR Capital Markets<br> Hans Mosesmann - Raymond James<br> Ruben Roy - Piper Jaffray<br> Quinn Bolton - Needham &amp; Company<br> Joe Moore - Morgan Stanley<br> Suji De Silva - Topeka Capital Markets<br> Stephen Chin - UBS</p> <p><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p>Welcome to the Broadcom Fourth Quarter 2014 Earnings Call. My name is Bakiba and I will be your operator for today's call. [Operator Instructions]. Please note that this conference is being recorded. I would now turn the call over to Peter Andrew. Peter Andrew, you may begin.</p> <p><strong>Peter Andrew</strong></p> <p>Thank you and good afternoon, everyone. Today's call will include prepared remarks by Scott McGregor, our President and Chief Executive Officer and Eric Brandt, our Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer. This call will include forward-looking statements which are subject to risks and uncertainties that could cause Broadcom's results to differ materially and adversely from management's current expectations.</p> <p>We encourage you to review the cautionary statements and risk factors contained in the earnings release which was furnished with the SEC today and is available on our website and in our most recent annual report on Form 10-K and subsequent reports on Form 10-Q. We undertake no obligation to revise or<span class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"> update publicly any forward-looking statement to reflect future events or circumstances. Additionally, throughout this call, we will be discussing certain non-GAAP financial measures.</span></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\">Today's earnings and the related current report on Form 8-K describe the differences between our non-GAAP and GAAP reporting and present a reconciliation between the two<span class=\"paywall-full-content no-summary-bullets invisible\"> for the periods reported in the release. Please also see the investor section of our website at Investors. Broadcom.com for a slide deck that includes additional information disclosed in accordance with SEC Regulation G. It is now my pleasure to introduce Broadcom's President and Chief Executive Officer, Scott McGregor.</span></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Scott McGregor</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Good afternoon and thanks for joining us. Broadcom had strong results in the December quarter. Revenue was at the high end of the guided range and non-GAAP EPS for the quarter came in ahead of first call at consensus. In the broadband and connectivity segment, revenues declined less than we initially expected. In broadband access, there is significant operator interest to upgrade last mile access technologies such as DSL and PON to the fastest speeds.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">In set-top box, developed markets are upgrading to new media server architectures and we're starting to see the first ultra HD boxes roll out. The decline in connectivity was also more modest than we initially expected due to the success of new phone launches, as well as increasing penetration of 802.11ac and 2x2 solutions. In infrastructure, our business declined as expected due to lower data center and service provider spending.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">For 2014, we delivered record revenues and record reportable segment profitability. Our BCG and ING revenue grew 6% while operating profit grew 25%, consistent with our goal of profitable growth. I'll go into these items in more detail later in the call, but first, I'll turn the call over to Eric for details on the fourth quarter results and on first quarter guidance.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Eric Brandt</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thanks, Scott. As Peter mentioned, please refer to the data breakout on the investor section of our website for additional information that will supplement my financial commentary. As previously discussed at our analyst day, we're now including stock-based compensation in our non-GAAP operating results, in addition to allocating it to our reportable segments. We decided to make this change to recognize-reflect all employee costs in our results and align with many investors' financial models.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Consistent with this, we\u2019ve recast our segments and other non-GAAP financial information in our 10-K and web financial statements for the current and prior periods. For the purposes of comparability with external estimates and prior guidance, we're also providing the comparable non-GAAP metrics excluding stock-based compensation in the following discussion. Going forward, we will guide gross margin and R&amp;D and SG&amp;A expenses that include stock-based compensation.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Moving to the financial overview. To summarize, Q4 revenue came in at $2.14 billion, down 5.2% sequentially and up 3.8% year-over-year. Excluding cellular base band revenue, reportable segment revenue was down 3% sequentially and up 10% year-over-year. Q4 non-GAAP gross margin was up 60 basis points from Q3 to 54.7%. Our Q4 non-GAAP gross margin now includes roughly 30 basis points of stock-based compensation.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Q4 GAAP gross margin was 52.8%. Q4 R&amp;D plus SG&amp;A expenses were down $46 million, including stock-based compensation. Q4 non-GAAP EPS, excluding stock-based compensation, was $0.90 a share or $0.03 above first call consensus of $0.87 per share. Including stock-based compensation, Q4 non-GAAP EPS was $0.76 a share. Q4 GAAP EPS was $0.64 a share which includes $0.09 of additional impairment and restructuring charges principally related to our exit of the cellular base band business. Cash flow from operations for Q4 was $633 million. Our cash and marketable securities balance at the end of the quarter was $6 billion.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Moving to revenue and gross margin. In December, we updated our guided range for Q4 revenue to between $2.075 billion and $2.15 billion. We delivered revenue right at the high end of that range at $2.143 billion. Our broadband and connectivity revenue came in ahead of expectations at $1.48 billion, down roughly 2% sequentially. Upside in the quarter was in wireless connectivity and broadband modems.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Revenue from our infrastructure and networking segment met our expectations of down sequentially at $625 million. Q4 non-GAAP gross margin was up 60 basis points from Q3 to 54.7% and includes roughly 30 basis points of stock-based compensation. This was at the midpoint of our guided range of 55% excluding stock-based compensation. Q4 GAAP gross margin was up from Q3 to 52.8%.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Moving to operating expenses. Total R&amp;D and SG&amp;A expenses were slightly above our revised guidance in December and down $46 million from Q3 levels, including stock-based compensation as a couple of unplanned tape-outs occurred late in the quarter. Going forward, non-GAAP and GAAP R&amp;D plus SG&amp;A should be the same and will be consolidated into a single estimate.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Moving to the balance sheet. Cash and marketable securities ended Q4 at $6 billion of which 48% is in the U.S.. Cash flow from operations was $633 million. During the quarter, we paid $72 million in dividends and repurchased 2.5 million shares of stock at a cost of $104 million. We announced an increase in our quarterly dividend by 17% to $0.14 per share. We also continue to target repurchasing $1 billion of stock in 2015, Q4 accounts receivable day sales outstanding were 34 days and net inventory turns were 7.6.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Moving to restructuring and impairment charges. In Q4, we recorded restructuring costs of $16 million and impairment charges of $14 million, as we continued to exit our wind down of our cellular base band business. We expect to record an additional $40 million of restructuring charges over the next 12 months primarily related to the closing or consolidation of 19 locations.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Moving to expectations, We currently expect net revenue in Q1 to be $2 billion plus or minus $75 million. From a segment perspective, we expect broadband and connectivity to be down and infrastructure networking to be roughly flat. We expect Q1 non-GAAP gross margin to be roughly flat to Q4 at 54.7% plus or minus 75 basis points and GAAP gross margin to be flat as well at 52.8% plus or minus 75 basis points.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">We expect R&amp;D and SG&amp;A expenses in Q1 to be up between $5 million and $25 million which, again, now includes stock-based compensation.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">And now I would like to turn the call back over to Scott to talk more about the state of the business.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Scott McGregor</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thanks, Eric. Starting with the broadband and connectivity business, our revenue came in at $1.475 billion down roughly 2% sequentially and better than we initially expected. Upside in the quarter was across the board, including set-top box, broadband access and particularly wireless connectivity. In set-top box, we're seeing growth in emerging markets and new technologies. Operators such as Dish in North America, Free in France and Tata in India have begun to offer ultra HD set-top boxes to their subscribers.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">We're expecting at least 15 operators across multiple regions to launch 4K television service in 2015. In broadband access, the race to Gigabit speeds in the home continues as telcos invest in G.fast and cable MSOs invest in DOCSIS 3.1, while both invest in high speed optical access. Broadcom is leading this transition with our first design wins with G.fast and 10-GPON already in place.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">In connectivity, we saw increased demand for newly introduced smartphones, combined with increasing adoption of new wireless technologies such as 802.11ac and 2x2 solutions that drive higher ASPs. 5G WiFi revenues reached a record high in the quarter and more than doubled for the year. We're seeing significant customer interest in our 4x4 multiuser MIMO 5G WiFi chip targeted for retail routers, broadband access gateways and set-top boxes. In addition, we're broadening our connectivity business beyond smartphones into adjacent markets, for example, we're powering both Denon and Harman Kardon's WiFi home audio systems.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">We've also received our first design win for our wireless charging solution. We continue to diversify into new markets such as Internet of Things, automotive, wearables and small cells. In the Internet of Things market, design activity remains high with our current products and we're in the process of refreshing our portfolio with purposeful products that are optimized specifically for different market segments. Registrations for our WICED Internet of Things platform have grown dramatically from 2000 at the beginning of 2014 to over 8000 now.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">We announced the expansion of our distribution channel with more than 40 new partners to expand our sales reach to Internet of Things customers. Lastly, small cell remains an emerging opportunity. We're ramping our newly launched LTE and TD-SCDMA solutions while maintaining our market-leading position in 3G. We're starting to see increasing adoption from carriers. For example, we're working with SpiderCloud, who recently announced they will be supplying Verizon for 4G enterprise small cells. Looking into Q1, we expect our broadband and connectivity business to be down sequentially.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Moving to infrastructure. Our infrastructure and networking group declined as expected, down 4% sequentially to $625 million. The data center segment was relatively stronger than the enterprise and service provider segments. In the data center market, we have a large number of customers in production with Trident II and are building a solid pipeline of design wins for Tomahawk. At 3.2 terabits per second, Tomahawk is the industry's highest bandwidth switching solution and has been shipped to over 15 different networking box makers, establishing an early lead over competitors. Longer term, we remain confident in growth drivers that include new build-outs and expansions of data centers, increasing data traffic at faster speeds and ASIC conversions to merchant solutions. In the service provider market, we're seeing broad adoption of our 28-nanometer heterogeneous knowledge-based processers.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">We also delivered version 2.0 of our OpenFlow SDN or software defined networking reference platform that delivers on the flexibility and control requirements for large scale carrier network deployments. Finally, we released an enhanced version of our broader reach Ethernet product that extends our automotive market opportunity beyond infotainment and driver assistance into telematics, satellite antennas and instrumentation clusters. We currently have design wins with five automakers and expect solid growth this year.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">As we look into Q1, we expect our infrastructure and networking business to be roughly flat sequentially. In summary, our broadband and connectivity and our infrastructure and networking segments performed well during the fourth quarter and we exceeded our expectations for both revenue and operating profits. 2014 has been the third consecutive year of double-digit growth for our infrastructure and networking business due to our leadership in the switch market.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Broadband and connectivity saw single digit growth in 2014 due to a strong position in the high end of the phone market and set-top box and access markets.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">This concludes our prepared comments and we're now ready for your questions. Bakiba, may we have the first question, please?</p> <p id=\"question-answer-session\" class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Question-and-Answer Session</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">[Operator Instructions]. Our first question is going to come from Vivek Arya out of Bank of America Merrill Lynch. Please go ahead with your question.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Vivek Arya</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you for taking my question and good execution on the cash generation side in Q4. When I look at the Q1 outlook implied for the broadband and connectivity segment, it shows sales down about 8%. Not that far off from the down 6%, 7% in prior years. Do you think, Scott, this business is back to seasonal trends, IE, the connectivity part has stabilized? Or do you still think there are some shoes to sort of drop on the connectivity side that could take somewhat longer to get back to more seasonal trends?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">I think our connectivity business is strong. We've had very good strength in the high end of the market, continue to do so. We've been able to migrate our customers to higher end solutions, including 802.11 AC and moving towards 2x2. Not all of our customers have moved to 2x2, so there's some opportunity to move there and we see other technologies becoming available as well. We're also broadening our technology portfolio in connectivity to include things like wireless charging and other technologies. So we see that business over the long term. I think this year will be potentially a little challenging.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">But over the long term, we see that as a growth business. In terms of seasonality, a little hard to predict there because it tends to be affected by the inventory and the consumption of some of our larger customers, but again, that's a real good busy think going forward.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Vivek Arya</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">And then as my follow-up on the infrastructure and networking business, it has been doing well for a long period of time. But when I look at Q4 and Q1, the implied growth rate is about 5% to 6% year-on-year. I think you had mentioned some good trends on the data center side, but slowdown on the carrier side. When do you see that business get back to your target, sort of double-digit growth rates? And what's going to be the catalyst? Is it new products? Does China LTE spending need to turn back up? When will we start to see your traditional growth trajectory in that business? Thank you.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Our infrastructure business is driven by a number of factors, they include certainly capital spending on the part of the larger carriers, it includes the build-outs of large data centers and then the overall enterprise upgrade as people move to higher speeds. We also introduced a number of new products and continue to push forward there. So all of those are the factors that drive growth and many of those, we don't control. But over the longer term, we do see that as a double-digit business and when it works out to exactly this year will again depend on those factors and it's hard for us to predict, but certainly we see that as a double-digit growth business over a multiple year period.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Vivek Arya</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">One quick one for Eric. In Q4, the buyback I believe was about 100 million, but I think you allocated 1 billion to this year. Should we expect that to be stretched out evenly across all the quarters or more frontend or backend loaded? Thank you.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Eric Brandt</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">I would say it really does depend on the stock price, but I would say our intention is to be more or less evenly distributed across the quarters, maybe a little bit more front end dependent. Depends on how the market's behaving.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. Our next question is going to come from Harlan Sur out of JPMorgan. Please go ahead with your question.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Harlan Sur</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Within broadband and connectivity and specifically I'm more focused on broadband, on the Q1 guide is this primarily seasonal declines? And then as you think primarily about 2015, what's the confidence level about driving growth in the broadband segment? And maybe some color on what products and end markets are going to be driving that growth. Is it going to be more set top box driven or more broadband access driven?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Eric Brandt</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">So Harlan, it's Eric. I'll answer the seasonality piece. Relative to broadband in Q4, it was actually a touch better than seasonal in Q4, on the strength of some key product launches in Q4 and while well within the standard deviation, a touch below the seasonal number in Q1. So you know, probably net pretty close together, but that's sort of the rough seasonal -- pretty close to seasonal when you look sort of at both quarters together.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Harlan, in terms of growth drivers, we've been benefiting from geographic expansion. We've talked about expanding into South America, into South Asia, into Africa, places like that that have been relatively new territories for us. So that's benefited us certainly in 2014 and I see that continuing into the next year. As we get further into the year, we'll see more of a pickup from the 4K HEVC opportunity. That's a multiyear kind of opportunity over the next 3 or 4 years, as I think a lot of, a lot of the MSOs and so forth will move to 4K and also on things like cable modem, we're seeing people move to DOCSIS 3.1. I think we'll see initial shipments this year, but that's more of a 2016 phenomenon when we'll see DOCSIS 3.1 start to real kick in. So we've got a set of growth drivers there and obviously we'll continue to broaden that portfolio and we have got some other businesses there including small cells and internet of things and other stuff that will drive that as well</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Harlan Surveillance</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Just a follow-up question for Eric on the OpEx front. And I'm certainly not complaining here. If you can help us understand what's driving the lower step-up in OpEx in Q1? Typically it's a $30 million to $40 million step-up. You're guiding it to grow only $15 million. And I think at analyst day you expected OpEx beyond Q1 to step up a little bit in Q2 due to more employee-related benefits and then kind of trend down Q3 and Q4. Is that how we should continue to think about it as well?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">So on the first point, Harlan, you're correct. The step-up in Q1 historically has been about $30 million to $35 million with the reduction in the number of people associated with our exit from the cellular base band. That number looks more like 25-ish million dollars. There is actually a pretty strong quarter in masks and prototyping costs as well, offset by solid expense management in Q1 and other areas. So that's why you see the lower number relative to what you would expect from the step-up. We continue to manage our expenses pretty tightly and going into Q1 we'll continue to do so.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">As you look across the rest of the year, bear in mind that Q1 really has only one month of the merit increase in the number, given the timing of when the merit increase is distributed. So you pick up the other two months in Q2, so typically it's up a little bit in Q2 as a result of that, just by itself. And then you're right, probably flat to down in the remaining quarters of the year as the fringe comes down and we sort of manage our costs pretty tightly. The only plus or minus could be just timing of tape-outs.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. Our next question is going to come from Ross Seymore from Deutsche Bank. Please go ahead with your question.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Ross Seymore</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Eric, this one's for you. On gross margin, can you talk a little bit about the puts and takes on why that would be flat in the first quarter? I would think from a mix-adjusted perspective, it would have risen. If there is any other detail you can provide there, I would appreciate it.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Eric Brandt</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Sure, Ross. It's a good question. There are two things going on in Q1 in terms of the guide. One is that there is some mix within mix, but actually, the gross margin would actually be up slightly in Q1 but for the absorption difference between Q4 and Q1 on the lower revenue. And that's about a 25 basis point impact. So if you use the same revenue or cost to quarters, we would be looking up 25 basis points.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Ross Seymore</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">So this is a utilization or a coverage issue, that mix isn't enough to offset that, I think?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Eric Brandt</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Well, no. Well that's what's making it flat. It would otherwise be up, so there's some benefit actually that would go into Q1 if you had the same revenue. And there's some mix within mix just on timing of things, but otherwise, actually it's slightly up in Q1 if the revenue were the same.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Ross Seymore</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">This is my follow-up, sticking on the expense side of the equation. I'm happy you guys are putting stock-base comp now into the numbers. I think it's a good higher quality number for us to look at. Can you talk a little bit about what you expect stock-based comp to do throughout this year and maybe as 2015 as a whole?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Eric Brandt</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Sure. So I expect in Q1 SBC, stock-based comp to be down a couple of million bucks Q4 to Q1 and then roughly flat plus or minus a couple of things over the course of the year for the rest of the year. So the pattern that we've had in the past, as we sort of move to our adjustment in stock-base comp, some of the changes again with less employees in the company, we should see a relatively flat stock-based comp number per quarter across the year.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. Our next question is going to come from Srini Pajjuri from CLSA Securities. Please go ahead with your question.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Srini Pajjuri</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Scott, on the connectivity side, can you talk about how you're feeling about your market share on the high end and also now that most of the 802.11 AC transition is done, what's going to drive the growth in this business as you look out to next one to two years?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">So I would characterize our market share in the high end of connectivity as very strong. We believe we're winning and hopefully will continue to win the majority of those designs based on very strong product execution. In terms of what drives revenue growth in that area going forward, it's true that many of the customers have now moved to 802.11 AC, but we see increasing numbers of diversity, antennas go in those boxes. They will move from 1x1 to 2x2 and even over that over time. Typically what you see in tablets or in laptops moves into cell phones as people look for higher connectivity performance. Also driving growth is the opportunity to add additional technologies. So for us it's an opportunity to grow share in NFC, wireless charging an