fly about 60 gigahertz WiFi, I thought your demos at CES were pretty compelling. Do you see this as the next generation of WiFi or is it really something different? And how might the market dynamics be different than what we saw in .ac?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">60 gigahertz is an interesting technology because of its high frequency, the opportunity to have very high bandwidth, yet it also has some challenges such it tends to be a little more line of sight or rely on scatter and reflection. So for example, it's blocked by the human body, it's blocked by a table or furniture and so it makes it difficult to use in many cases. I think you're going to see the use cases are a number. I think you'll see some cable replacement where you'll replace short range cable connections, you know, like a high-speed USB kind of connection. I think you'll see it for high-speed data backup or connectivity where you can assure a line of sight. So those will be opportunities for it there. I don't think it will replace wireless LAN. Wireless LAN has an incredible range. We've gotten the range of wireless LAN up well over the initial 100 meter spec to 2 or 3 times that and the data rate is very high on wireless LAN these days. So I think 60 gigahertz will tend to be specialized applications, certainly not a replacement for wireless LAN and I wouldn't be surprised if you'll see devices have both in them.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. Our next question is going to come from Hans Mosesmann from Raymond James. Please go ahead with your question.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Hans Mosesmann</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Scott, can you give us an update on your [inaudible] multi-core processor, you didn't mention anything in your prepared remarks, but if there is an effort tell us the strategic importance of it or maybe you don't have to be in business, maybe you can give us your comments. Thanks.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Broadcom has a broad range of ARM processers that we do internally. We have ARM processers in quite a few of our devices actually and many of them are multiprocessor. So for example, our set-top boxes have very, very strong multiprocessor ARM cores in them. We also see an opportunity in the network space for network processers and we've made a good effort there and we've announced a processor architecture which is definitely super-high performance there that competes with the highest performance processers you can get anywhere. And again, the challenge with multiprocessors is not just the speed of the processor itself, but the overall system performance because you have to balance the buses for the data and the instructions and the I/O on those devices.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">So we'll look to scaling that up at the very high end in our infrastructure and networking space, as well as deploy it through broadband and things like set-top boxes where you run it for applications and then also in things like Internet of Things. We have ARM processers there where we use them for running the applications. Those tend to be very low power, very small footprint devices. So we have probably almost two orders of magnitude in size of these ARM cores that we use across our whole product family.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. Our next question is going to come from Ruben Roy from Piper Jaffray. Please go ahead.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Ruben Roy</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Scott, I just had a quick one on one of your comments, the 2x2 WiFi. You said you doubled the revenue in 2014, I believe. I'm wondering in terms of the mix of design activity that you're seeing there, how far along are you in smartphones and are those products also bleeding into some other end markets? And if you could talk a little bit about if there is a margin implication there. Is it a positive margin implication as you move 2x2? Thanks.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Yes, I can't give you color to the extent of specific customers, but we're definitely seeing sort of the move from 1x1 to 2x2 and we\u2019re going to see some customers go to 3x3 or other kind of things. There is definitely an opportunity to keep upping the performance of wireless LAN, whether it's AC in different configurations or a new AX technology going forward that has an opportunity for much better performance in crowded environments and other things.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">So I think that for many, many years, we see lots of opportunity to increase margin or increase competitiveness by adding additional technologies and combining them. And then of course one of the things that Broadcom is especially good at is making all of these technologies play well together. So it's one thing to have a great technology here, but it's another thing to make it work well with all the other radio technologies you have in the product and that's a specialty of ours and works especially well in our combo chips. And so you'll see us broaden our combo chips to include new technologies and more advanced technologies going forward and to your point, does that help on margin, yes it does to the extent we can fill new technologies there.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. Our next question is going to come from Quinn Bolton from Needham &amp; Company. Please go ahead with your question.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Quinn Bolton</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">One for Scott, one for Eric. Scott, just wanted to know, a number of your competitors in the switch space have announced Tomahawk class switches, some of which are programmable. Just wondering if you're seeing any real change in the competitive landscape at the high end of the data center switch market. And then for Eric, you talked about increasing at Analyst Day, increasing U.S. cash flow from 30% to 40% to 45% as you adjust the tax. Is there a new tax guidance you can give us for 2015? Or are you still working through taxes? Thanks.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">I think in the high end switch, what you've seen from Broadcom is taking a series of high end switches that we did in a single family, the Trident family and now really broadening it into multiple families of high end switches. So you see parallel product families of Tomahawk and Trident and then all of the other switches we do below that, the whole XGS family. So we've got a tremendous family there and the nice thing is there is great software compatibility across those and some of our competitors like to position theirs as potentially programmable and ours not.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Our switches are all programmable and customizable. So that's a misimpression that some people have gotten. We haven't seen much competition on the high end and we have certainly seen announcements, but to my knowledge, they haven't sampled yet. So our experience is generally from the time you actually sample and get it in a customer's hands, it's a year or 18 months before you see shipment revenue on that. And I mentioned in my earlier remarks we have something like 15 different customers who are building products based on Tomahawk today. So very, very different I think view of the competitors versus where we're in that space and Broadcom has executed extremely well there.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Eric Brandt</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Quinn, it's Eric. I believe I mentioned on analyst day, you should presume that the tax rate moves up by roughly 1 point this year. That's about it.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. Our next question is going to come from Joe Moore from Morgan Stanley. Please go ahead with your question.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Joe Moore</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">You talked at Analyst Day about a number of initiatives to sort of realign management compensation and doing things like charging at the segment levels, the stock option expense, things like that. Just wondering what changes you think now that you've sort of gone back to the [Technical Difficulty] is that going to result in lower stock issuance over time from stock comp expense? And just any other changes that you see as you've started to implement those changes.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Eric Brandt</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Joe, it's Eric. Look, I think we view stock-based compensation as part of our employee-base costs. We mention that we're looking at the balance between cash and equity and I think what you'll see when we publish that, we will publish a lower number than what you saw last year by the amount that we were talking about on Analyst Day. We're targeting the number to be sub-4%. We think there's an opportunity to do that and do that relatively quickly.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you Our next question is going to come from Suji De Silva from Topeka Capital Markets. Please go ahead with your question. </p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Suji De Silva</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Question about the enterprise data center business, I presume the strength there is coming from corporate as well as some of the cloud customers, you have a very strong position with. I'm wondering if there is potential for that business to be lumpy as it continues to ramp up in 2015 or whether you expect a more steady track there?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Well, it's always somewhat lumpy. I think the data center business is driven increasingly by these large cloud data centers that are being deployed. You see there is like 10 companies that are driving a huge percentage of all the data center expansion. And we also see a lot of the corporate guys either outsourcing to guys like that or when they build a new data center, they build it more in a cloud architecture sort of an in-sourced cloud, if you will. So definitely some lumpiness, but we do see that as a strong trend for us going forward.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. Our next question is going to come from [inaudible] from MacQuarie. Please go ahead with your question.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Unidentified Analyst</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">I had a question for Scott about the content wearables. It sound like you're getting good design traction there. So should we think about content in that market segment similar to that as feature phones, smartphones or tablets? And then Eric, on the segment operating model, on the new disclosure it kind of looks like the networking business has similar operating margins to broadband. So as we think about OpEx growth on a segment level going forward and subsequently how should we think about operating leverage?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">The content and wearables, it really depends on exactly what we win in the device, but generally, the connectivity is simpler, it's lower power, it's smaller footprint, so generally tends to have a lower ASP than in the -- certainly the high end smartphones that we've seen.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Eric Brandt</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">And then on the question on the segment operating margins, I mean, if you look at the year what you'll see in the K, actually they are not the same. The infrastructure business with stock-based comp will be about 27% and the broadband business about 20%. So they are still structurally different in terms of their operating margins in terms of the businesses. And then I would say in terms of operating expense deployment literally it's a project by project and ROI by ROI opportunity basis. I don't know that we think specifically about the businesses, although we're trying to manage both of those businesses to a set of targets relative to operating margin which would determine the amount of R&amp;D that they would be allocated or incremental R&amp;D they would be allocated based on their ability to hit that target.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. And our next question is going to come from Stephen Chin from UBS. Please go ahead with your question.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"question\">Stephen Chin</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Eric, if I could ask a little more color on the increased use of the distribution partners. I know that you guys have used some of them in the past, but just with the increase recently. I was wondering if you could talk a bit more about, number one, is that all still being, with the sales there, is that still being recognized on the sell through basis for all of them? And also are there certain product areas or product lines that you're focusing on in using where you can sell through that distribution channel? And whether or not that helps increase your visibility on orders or not?</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong><span class=\"answer\">Scott McGregor</span></strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Yes, Stephen. So you're right. You'll see that in the K that excluding fulfillment distributors have actually over the last three years gone up about 4 points in our mix relative to distribution. Much of that is our strategy to sort of go after some of the longer tail opportunities in the business. Certainly things like IoT lend themselves to things that run through distribution, where our size and nature of our support network don't do it. So we've talked about sort of expanding our distribution footprint and you can actually now begin to see it in the numbers.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">In terms of the way we recognize revenue, we do still and have for as long as I've been here, recognize revenue on a sell-through basis. So what we ship to the distributors is not recorded as revenue until they actually sell out. In terms of visibility, I think it's a segmentation question for the business and using distribution to sort of segment the part of the market that we wouldn't naturally have good visibility to and then to leverage those partners to use us where they need to, to broaden the footprint and so between distribution and some of the things Scott mentioned in terms of the website relative to WICED, I think we're getting good traction on moving those things forward.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you. We have no further questions at this time. I would like to turn the call back over to Scott McGregor.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Scott McGregor</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thanks everyone for joining today. 2014 was a pivotal year for Broadcom, in which the company made a number of important profit enhancing business decisions and we refocused on our areas of strength. We believe we're a stronger company now as a result of this. I would like to thank our employees and all of our investors for their support as we made this transition. With that, thank you very much and have a good day.</p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\"><strong>Operator</strong></p> <p class=\"paywall-full-content invisible no-summary-bullets\">Thank you, ladies and gentlemen. This concludes today's conference. Thank you for participating. You may now disconnect.</p>", "twitContent": "$AVGO - Broadcom Corporation's (BRCM) CEO Scott McGregor on Q4 2014 Results -- Earnings Call Transcript. https://seekingalpha.com/article/2867236-broadcom-corporations-brcm-ceo-scott-mcgregor-on-q4-2014-results-earnings-call-transcript?source=tweet ", "innerMarketing": null, "marketingBullet": "", "isReit": false, "videoData": null, "marketingBulletVariant": null, "marketingBio": null}, "relationships": {"author": {"data": {"id": "44211", "type": "author"}}, "sentiments": {"data": []}, "primaryTickers": {"data": [{"id": "14539", "type": "tag"}]}, "secondaryTickers": {"data": []}, "otherTags": {"data": [{"id": "96991", "type": "tag"}, {"id": "17994", "type": "tag"}, {"id": "49", "type": "tag"}, {"id": "326", "type": "tag"}, {"id": "18018", "type": "tag"}]}, "coAuthors": {"data": []}, "presentations": {"data": []}, "updates": {"data": []}, "corrections": {"data": []}}, "links": {"self": "/article/2867236-broadcom-corporations-brcm-ceo-scott-mcgregor-on-q4-2014-results-earnings-call-transcript", "canonical": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/2867236-broadcom-corporations-brcm-ceo-scott-mcgregor-on-q4-2014-results-earnings-call-transcript", "uriImage": "https://static.seekingalpha.com/assets/og_image_1200-29b2bfe1a595477db6826bd2126c63ac2091efb7ec76347a8e7f81ba17e3de6c.png", "schemaImage": null}}, "included": [{"id": "44211", "type": "author", "attributes": {"company": null, "slug": "sa-transcripts", "userId": 101639, "tagId": 96991, "image": {"small": "https://static3.seekingalpha.com/images/users_pr